article.description:
Tamecka Dixon scored 13 of her 19 points in the second half as the visiting Los Angeles Sparks dug their way out of a 22-point first-half deficit to defeat the San Antonio Silver
Stars 67-58.
article.headline: Sparks ignite with second-half surge
article.linkText: Sparks rally from 22 down to win in San Antonio
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) --  As well as the San Antonio Silver Stars
played in the first half of Thursday's game against Los Angeles,
the Sparks played even better in the second half.

Tamecka Dixon scored 13 of her 19 points in the second half as
the Sparks dug their way out of a deep deficit to defeat the Silver
Stars 67-58.

"We knew we couldn't get it all back at once, but we wanted to
chip away at the lead," Dixon said. "We knew if we were more
aggressive we would have a chance."

The Sparks rallied from 22 points down in the first half, tying the WNBA record set by the Utah Starzz in a 70-62 comeback victory over Phoenix on Aug. 20, 1999.

The Silver Stars (5-8)  were outscored 43-17 by the Sparks (12-2) 43-17 in the second
half. Los Angeles scored 20 of its second-half points in the paint
while limiting San Antonio to only three baskets inside.

"L.A. is a second-half team," said San Antonio coach Candi
Harvey. "We allowed them to do what they do best, and that's push
the ball."
	   
San Antonio made only six of its 36 attempts in the second half
after going 11-for-24 in the first 20 minutes.
	   
"We didn't start the second half with the same intensity,"
said San Antonio guard Marie Ferdinand, who ended with 15 points,
all but two coming in the first half. "They were the aggressors
... We were passive."
	   
DeLisha Milton added 14 points and 13 rebounds for Los Angeles.
Lisa Leslie, who sat out most of the first half in foul trouble,
finished with a season-low nine points on 3-for-16 shooting.
	   
Margo Dydek led the Silver Stars with 16 points and 10 rebounds,
while Adrienne Goodson contributed 14.
	   
San Antonio led 41-24 at the break but didn't score its first
points of the second half until Dydek made a short turnaround
jumper with 13:38 remaining.
	   
Los Angeles steadily pulled closer until a breakaway layup by
Milton off a steal gave the Sparks a 52-51 lead with 6:10
remaining.
	   
"We started off and got a few steals, and that really got it
rolling for us," said Sparks guard Nikki Teasley.
	   
Early on, it appeared as if San Antonio was going to win in a rout.
	   
A 15-footer by Leslie tied the score at 6 about three minutes
into the game, and then the Silver Stars went on a 15-0 run during
which Leslie committed three fouls and went to the bench for the
rest of the half.
	   
The Silver Stars' increased their lead to 37-15 on a turnaround
jumper by Dydek with 3:34 remaining in the half.
